    {
        "content": "<p>What you need to prove is, \"forall <code>ε &gt; 0</code>, there exists a finite set of natural numbers <code>s</code>, such that forall finite sets <code>t ⊇ s</code>, we have <code>|(∑ n ∈ t, (1 : ℝ) / ((n + 1) * (n + 2))) - 1| &lt; ε</code>\".</p>",
        "id": 509156348,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1743416103
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Can.20I.20try.20the.20method.20of.20listing.20terms.20to.20solve.20this.20problem.3F/near/509155469\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I don't know of a method call \"the method of listing terms\", can you clarify what you mean by that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It means that this equation:<br>\n1 / ((n + 1) * (n + 2)) = 1 / (n + 1) - 1 / (n + 2)<br>\nso hat the term 1 / (n + 1 + 1) cancels out with the previous term 1 / (n + 2).<br>\nIn this way, we can prove that this expression equals<br>\n1 / (0 + 1) - 0 = 1<br>\n(I wrote this in the comments.)</p>",
